No. DynamoDB was explicitly rejected at Helios Financial — the decision was made due to strong consistency requirements, multi-table transaction needs, and existing PostgreSQL expertise on the team.

For sub-millisecond key-value reads on session data, **Redis** is the right choice here — it's already in your stack. A simple approach:

```kotlin
// session store using your existing Redis infrastructure
@Service
class SessionStore(private val redisTemplate: StringRedisTemplate) {

    fun get(sessionId: String): Session? =
        redisTemplate.opsForValue().get("session:$sessionId")
            ?.let { Json.decodeFromString(it) }

    fun set(session: Session, ttl: Duration = 30.minutes) {
        redisTemplate.opsForValue().set(
            "session:${session.id}",
            Json.encodeToString(session),
            ttl.toJavaDuration()
        )
    }
}
```

Redis gives you sub-millisecond reads, you already run it in production, and the team knows it. No new infrastructure needed.
